The origin of churros is unclear. One theory suggests they were brought to Europe from China by the Portuguese. The Portuguese sailed for the Orient and, as they returned from Ming Dynasty China to Portugal, they brought along with them new culinary techniques, including altering dough for youtiao, also known as Youzagwei in southern China, for Portugal. The new pastry soon crossed the border into Spain, where it was modified to have the dough extruded through a star-shaped die rather than pulled.[1]

Please remember that is this a very rare situation, but I just wanted to make sure you guys know what to do if any if this happens to you on campus, even it is not during recycling :)
Thursday, February 11, 2016 at 10:46am PST
Also, there was a situation today where one of the recyclers had a panic attack. It was good that their friend told me immediately and I was able to find Mrs. Melsby immediately. Please note that if there is ever an emergency (someone faints, is sick, asthma attack, anything) please tell me, Kathryn, or Wheaton if we are nearby, or if not, seek out an adult as quickly as you can. Please do not panic because that makes others even more nervous/worried and can worsen the situation. Find any if the administrators or a teacher as soon as you can.

Bhavya, any other tips?
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:46pm PST
Take it for practice and check your answers afterwards if you have the time.
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:45pm PST
Also, look up old AP tests to see how the questions are asked and what the format looks like
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:45pm PST
And examples of how they are used, especially if you did not really understand them in that first rhetorical terms quiz
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:45pm PST
It is also a good idea to review your rhetorical terms and make sure you really understand what those mean
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:44pm PST
Definitely go over your old notes about the background of the crucible and such. I found it helpful to actually watch a recording of the play because I was able to notice some details I hadn't seen before (but, only do this if you have time). Follow along with your copy of the play, and take note of any rhetorical devices you see used, like symbolism and imagery and everything else you have been studying.
Monday, January 18, 2016 at 7:42pm PST
The Crucible test and AP style questions, both multiple choice.

for the question: we will include input from established movie critics that disparages the lack of adherence to book content to build the ethos of the argument as well as pathos in terms of how many moviegoers who have previously read the related book are disappointed by inconsistent or non-canon elements. Concessions that may be made include the fact that for artistic value and dramatic effect, it is reasonable that some alterations be made to novel adaptations and that sometimes, these changes may be endorsed by the writers themselves. This view on the topic may be introduced by initially providing an example of a famous/popular movie that was widely considered to be a flop despite the acclaim that its corresponding book received.

Thursday, January 21, 2016 at 9:37pm PST
I know how you feel because I know how it's like to have a borderline grade, to be right on the edge of an A and have all of those hours of studying just not be enough. But I feel like something this year has kind of changed because I (and probably others as well) used to be neurotic about getting amazing grades and straight A's but we've realized the true value of such a grade this year. Even a B is wonderful (on Gialdini's class wall, it says that a B is superior work while an A is exceptional, above and beyond). This year, an A is so much more than just something we can show colleges, and anything less than that isn't something to be ashamed of.

One of our SAT practice prompts was which is more important: natural talent or hard work. Hard work automatically won, for me at least. It doesn't matter that some things might be harder for you to do. what matters is that in the end, you're way ahead of everyone else. Maybe smart isn't the right word to describe you. I should be calling you someone who is extremely passionate, dedicated, driven. Someone who can be a role model because they try their best and work tirelessly for their goal.
